[When Burundi submitted to the OIE its immediate notification of a PPR outbreak (the 1st outbreak, in the central-situated Gitega province) on 11 Jan 2018, the start of the outbreak was given as 1 Jan 2018 and the reason for notification -- "First occurrence of a listed disease in the country." In Burundi's earlier annual reports, PPR was included in the list of diseases that were not reported during the addressed year (and not as "never reported"). The quoted view of FAO and OIE experts "that the presence of the disease in Burundi before the large outbreak could not be ruled out" is rather plausible. According to the 2017 annual reports from Burundi's neighbouring countries, in Rwanda PPR was referred to as "suspected (not confirmed)"; in Tanzania, Uganda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, PPR was "present".

Links to Burundi's immediate OIE notification (posted in 20180113.5555369), to the 6 follow-up reports, and to an interactive map presenting their locations throughout the country, are available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?fupser=&dothis=&reportid=25644.

According to the most recent (no. 6) follow-up report submitted, the accumulated PPR statistics, as of 6 Aug 2018, were the following:

Total outbreaks = 8 (submitted)
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Sheep and goats / 128 855 / 7458 / 3838 / 0 / 0

It would be interesting to note if any new PPR outbreaks have been observed in Burundi since 6 Aug 2018.

The information on mass vaccination covering the entire small ruminant population by 30 May 2028 is encouraging indeed. According to OIE's data, this population included, in 2017, about 1.752 million goats and 0.208 million sheep.

The OIE and the FAO, in their joint strategy (see http://www.oie.int/en/animal-health-in-the-world/ppr-portal/gsce/) for control and eradication of PPR, have set the goal of eradicating the disease by 2030. More information is available at the OIE Peste des Petits Ruminants Portal, http://www.oie.int/en/animal-health-in-the-world/ppr-portal/. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map: Burundi: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6220160,172.]
